What should it do, the ČSSD? The Czech Social Democrats in Prague know neither Voldemort nor the &quot;pastry shop&quot;.
The new councilors of the capital from the ranks of the ČSSD will obviously have to overcome certain language barriers in order to be able to understand their old and new colleagues from the ODS in the Prague Council and in the city council.
The newspaper Aktuálně.cz asked members of the new ČSSD council how they speak the notorious slang that has become commonplace in recent years, when the current coalition partners in Prague were at the helm.
The coded vocabulary introduced by Prague&#39;s political elite in the past era by Mayor Pavel Bém is borrowed from some of the most well-known actors, situations and causes.
Surprisingly, the new councils were somewhat in the dark about these new terms.
At least that&#39;s what they claim.
&quot;Who is Voldemort?&quot;
&quot;No idea.&quot;
&quot;I&#39;m more of a newcomer to Prague politics,&quot; said Lukáš Kaucký, the new councilor for culture, in response to the &quot;sponsor&#39;s vocabulary&quot; test.
But councilman Karel Březina - a political veteran - reacted in a similar way.
For example, the term &quot;golf hole&quot;.
&quot;That&#39;s the only expression you&#39;ve given me here that I use from time to time.&quot;
&quot;Otherwise I don&#39;t think much of slang.&quot;
From the vocabulary published by the daily Aktuálně.cz in June this year ahead of the ODS election congress, the editors selected six terms, primarily those notoriously associated with the Prague magistrate.
The Social Democrats should define the terms &quot;Voldemort&quot;, &quot;Prague&#39;s biggest golf hole&quot;, &quot;go to the pastry shop&quot;, &quot;bull&#39;s neck&quot;, &quot;treason of the capital&quot; and &quot;cover up&quot;.
Three Prague councilors agreed to the test, the fourth - Antonín Weinert, the future head of the Prague school system - initially promised to take part in the discussion, but then didn&#39;t even pick up the phone.
