In agreement with Březina, however, he claims that he got this knowledge from the newspaper rather than that this vocabulary is his own.
In fact, judging by the test takers, there doesn&#39;t seem to be any similarly naturalized slang among the Social Democrats.
&quot;I also asked my colleagues, but obviously we really don&#39;t have anything like that.&quot;
&quot;We call each other by name, sometimes we also use abbreviations or nicknames,&quot; says the chairman of the Prague ČSSD Petr Hulínský - casually called &quot;Hulda&quot; by his party comrades.
&quot;I was called Bříza (Birch) at school, but I don&#39;t know if my colleagues call me that too,&quot; Karel Březina tells us about his nickname.
The newspaper Deník Aktuálně.cz tried the name and lo and behold - it works.
Councilor Weinert is friendly to the party comrades as &quot;grandfather&quot; or less friendly as &quot;old man&quot;, the representative Miroslav Poche, who drew attention to himself before the elections through machinations in party sponsorship, is called &quot;Igráček&quot; (known Czech Lego -figure) called.
Nicknames are the only thing the Social Democrats allow in intra-party parlance.
Hulínský reportedly doesn&#39;t like being called &quot;Hulda&quot;, but Deník Aktuálně.cz registered another nickname of the Prague chairman.
His nickname &quot;Doctor of Baton Rights&quot; is said to have something to do with the fact that Petr Hulínský earned his Doctor juris title at the Bratislava Police Academy.
The government wants to stop the torture of &quot;witches&quot; and has published a brochure
Women labeled witches in Burkina Faso tend to share some common societal characteristics.
They tend to belong to the older generation, they cannot find work - for example for health reasons, they are single and have no children.
If one of these women &quot;becomes&quot; a witch, she is strictly isolated so that she cannot become dangerous to the rest of the village.
&quot;Men are rarely affected by this fate.&quot;
&quot;Even young and healthy women are spared this because they help with the work and give birth to children,&quot; describes a nun who takes care of more than 100 women in a special home in the capital of the West African state of Burkina Faso communities were expelled.
The local government has now decided to take action against this abnormal &quot;social measure&quot;.
And for this reason published a brochure intended to stop the &quot;hunting of witches&quot;.
But there is a catch.
&quot;More than 70 percent of all adults in Burkina Faso cannot read,&quot; the newspaper &quot;derStandard&quot; pointed out to the dilemma of written education.
Being accused of witchcraft is also common in other African countries.
In Ghana, the neighboring country of Burkina Faso, 27-year-old Ammy Hemmahová was tortured to death by three women and two men - they poured petroleum over her and simply set her on fire.
The BBC server, among others, also reported on this incident.
However, the perpetrators claimed it was just a combination of unfortunate circumstances.
According to their version, oil used for ritual anointing was ignited.
And that was after the group tried to &quot;exorcise an evil spirit&quot; from the woman.
The isolation of &quot;witches&quot; support the people here regardless of their education.
&quot;Der Standard&quot; quoted a 42-year-old entrepreneur from Burkina Faso: &quot;Eaters of human souls were a danger then as now,&quot; he said.
While the government in Burkina Faso is at least trying to defuse the witch hunt, the Gambian president got involved last year.
&quot;President Yahya Jammeh launched a monstrous witch hunt after the death of his aunt, claiming they had a hand in her death and were now trying to kill the President himself with black magic.&quot;
&quot;To do this, he called for the help of shamans from nearby Guinea, who, accompanied by police officers, soldiers and the president&#39;s bodyguards, forcibly kidnapped women and men who had been arrested at random from Gambian villages and brought them to the president&#39;s farm in Kanilai,&quot; said the organization Amnesty International in their report.
At the farm, incarcerated people were forced to drink a decoction of plants with hallucinogenic effects, which also caused intestinal and kidney problems.
Two of the arrested people did not survive their stay on the farm.
The nearly 1,000 prisoners were only released due to international pressure.
A tenant of Bakala: He heats the oven - but still pays higher rent
An elderly, stocky man is leaving the client center of the RPG Byty company of &quot;coal baron&quot; Zdeněk Bakala, the largest private owner of rented apartments in the Czech Republic.
Under his arm is a folder with three new leases for three apartments: for his own apartments and those of his daughters and his son, who is currently serving a prison sentence.
All three have just had their rent increased as part of the so-called &quot;deregulation&quot;.
Instead of renting 3,500 kroner a month, the son will shell out 4,100 kroner next year for a two-room apartment with a kitchen in the second category.
&quot;And there isn&#39;t even hot running water in the apartment and you have to heat it in a simple coal stove,&quot; he angrily taps his finger on his son&#39;s new lease, which he has authority to sign.
&quot;But what - I signed it,&quot; he explains, half annoyed and half resigned.
The civic association BytyOKD.cz, which called the new lease terms &quot;incorrect and immoral&quot;, advises tenants to simply not sign the new contracts and to wait until December 7, when they intend to publish instructions on how to counter such contracts.
But the man just waves it off.
&quot;One says this, the other that,&quot; he scowls.
The Ostrava region is thus becoming a large &quot;deregulation laboratory&quot;.
After the New Year, this deregulation will apply to most rental apartments in the Czech Republic, whose tenants have not yet been paying market rents.
Aktuálně.cz therefore decided to visit this &quot;laboratory&quot; in person.
The RPG waiting room in Havířov is one of four in the Ostrava region and is already packed at 9 am this Tuesday.
Right next to the door are the bodyguards of a security agency and with her a call device.
&quot;Rent 2011&quot;, a special button lights up on the touchscreen.
Tap it briefly and the device spits out a number slip.
We have barely deciphered the number &quot;157&quot; and it beeps on the large display on the ceiling of the waiting room.
Half a second later it&#39;s your turn.
A little later, an elderly couple enters the waiting room to ask about the rent, but the rush in the waiting room is apparently not about the new rent.
Most people are here to solve the usual problems - repair requests, insurance issues and the like.
From mid-November, the envelopes with the new leases will flutter into the mailboxes of most of the tenants of the 44,000 apartments in the RPG portfolio in the Ostrava region.
In the letter, RPG Byty proposes a rent increase of around 15 to 38 percent.
The special counter for the new rentals in the client center has been open since November 18th.
&quot;The campaign has been running for a little over a week, which means it&#39;s just the beginning,&quot; the women behind the counter reply after a moment&#39;s hesitation when the &quot;client&quot; turns out to be a journalist.
Deregulation and Bakala&#39;s former miners&#39; homes are hot topics.
Before the elections, Ostrava-born parliamentary vice-president Lubomír Zaorálek from the ČSSD took up this topic quite loudly, no wonder that the newspapers are full of it today.
&quot;I want a new floor from you for twenty years.&quot;
&quot;They couldn&#39;t even change a damaged toilet seat,&quot; the man mentioned at the beginning vents.
So far, according to the employees, it is mainly pensioners who are queuing at the counter to make sure that they are really getting the promised rent discount that RPG promises them if they sign the special offer in good time.
The other tenants who sign the new lease by December 15 should also be able to benefit from a February rent that is reduced by half.
So far, however, the &quot;de-regulation desk&quot; in Havířov has been anything but overwhelmed with inquiries.
&quot;Of yesterday&#39;s 360 clients, only about 40 to 50 were here because of the rent in 2011,&quot; estimate the clerks.
RPG offers individual rental agreements both on its websites and on wall boards where it seems necessary.
However, if the tenants do not agree on the new rent, it will be determined by an independent court.
&quot;This is not intended to be a threat, but is to be understood as information about the only possible and completely legitimate legal course of action,&quot; explains RPG on its website.
&quot;Nobody goes to court here,&quot; says one of the employees at RPG Byty, and a man on the street in front of the client center agrees, at least in part.
&quot;I have a pension of 13,000 (kroner), of which I have 5,000 left for food, where should I get the money for a court case,&quot; he says.
Then the employee becomes insecure.
&quot;Let&#39;s see.&quot;
&quot;Mr. Zaorálek tells them through the media not to sign and so people are still waiting,&quot; she says.
Regulated rent will end in most of the Czech Republic by New Year 2011 and according to RPG Byty the rent increase is an economic necessity.
&quot;The current level of rent is not even enough to maintain the housing fund,&quot; argues Pavel Klimeš, the director of the housing portfolio of the company RPG Byty, and the neglect of the housing fund criticized by the angry tenants is the main reason, according to homeowners the rent increase.
During the years between 2005 and 2010, RPG was able to invest four billion in the apartments from the rents received, in the four years from 2011 to 2014 it should be 5.2 billion.
On the large-format LCD display on the ceiling opposite the upholstered armchairs in Havířov&#39;s waiting room, a few pieces of information flash in red every now and then.
&quot;Rent increases in 2011 of 15% or less concern 31,200 apartments, that is more than 90% of RPG&#39;s apartments.&quot;
&quot;This always means a maximum of CZK 7.50 per square meter per month,&quot; reads the LCD monitor.
The rent increases by 38 percent only for 400 apartments from the RPG portfolio.
&quot;These cases are about raising extremely low rents of CZK 19.66 per square meter,&quot; RPG argues.
With 2,600 apartments, the rent will remain at the same level next year.
RPG Byty promises that deregulation won&#39;t skyrocket rents, but will happen gradually over four and eight years.
What&#39;s more - the company imposes another obligation on itself: all income from the rent increase (see diagram) the company wants to put back into the apartments, especially in heat savings - in new windows and thermal insulation.
But - primarily, these should benefit those people who sign the agreements on the rent increase.
The architects realized that the office also includes a kindergarten
The Avriopoint office building in Brno is the new headquarters of the Arch.Design company.
But who would expect a mini kindergarten here, with everything that goes with it: colorful walls, creative furniture, lots of toys and even a mini playground on the outdoor terrace.
This kindergarten has been available to Arch.Design employees since last year.
The design and architectural office Arch.Design, from whose studios come a number of well-known Brno buildings, counted on the premises for its company mini-kindergarten from the very first drafts for the new Avriopoint building.
With foresight, because most of his 90 employees are in the baby boom age and the company is keen to get the designers and architects back to work as quickly as possible.
Together with the possibility of shortened working hours, the kindergarten is another bonus that Arch.Design has to offer its employees in the concept of their social program.
This makes it easier for the civil engineers and architects to reconcile their demanding job and childcare.
The mini-kindergarten is an original idea of the Arch.Design employees and with the support of the management they managed to win funding from the European Union and the Ministry of Labor and Social Affairs for their project.
The company mini-kindergarten is financed by the Operational Program Human Resources and Employment Policy from the European Social Fund and the state budget of the Czech Republic.
Thanks to this funding (subsidies of CZK 2.8 million), the necessary facilities and equipment could be procured and qualified staff and operation will be provided for a period of 2 years.
After the funds have been exhausted (2 years), the Arch.Design company is obliged to continue operating the mini-kindergarten for a further 3 years at its own expense.
The preparation of this project took a whole year, with the Economy Rating company providing active help in processing the application.
The children are cared for full-time by qualified staff - a nurse and a kindergarten teacher. Children without age restrictions can attend the kindergarten, although most of them are over three years old.
And since this is a mini kindergarten, only 5 children are allowed to be present at the same time, but several children take turns throughout the day.
The day care center is flexibly tailored to the needs of the parents, the children of all employees have the same rights in relation to the use of the day care center - regardless of the company hierarchy and their respective position.
Although it is about individual upbringing and care, the content of the program in the mini-kindergarten is nevertheless comparable to the framework program of pre-school education.
The children don&#39;t just play here, but above all they are offered excellent instruction - from basic knowledge to pre-school classes, along with learning English.
The classroom is not only equipped with toys and creative games, but also with a calculator that is available for the children.
What&#39;s more - the presence of small children in the company contributes to a friendly and positive company environment.
The parents can take a look at the children at any time and this eliminates the stress of late picking up the children from a kindergarten far away.
Parents therefore use their working hours more productively.
No wonder that natural and loyal employer-employee relationships develop here.
Arch.Design has thus ranked among Czech companies that offer clear benefits when recruiting new employees, are family-friendly and use such programs to strengthen their personal marketing.
A bone house still fascinates after 100 years. Check out the interiors of Gaudi
The roof looks like the back of a prehistoric lizard, the stairs like the spine of a dinosaur and the balconies are gaping fish mouths.
This is Catalan architect Antonio Gaudi&#39;s Casa Batlló in Barcelona.
The house with its organic shapes was nicknamed &quot;Bone House&quot; by local residents.
Organic forms, wild colors, the unusual use of stone, shards of tile and mosaics, the facades resembling scales and ubiquitous soft lines, all these are typical features of Antonio Gaudi&#39;s Art Nouveau.
The facade of the house plays with dreamy lines, tender colors and textures that are reminiscent of nature and living beings.
Only on closer inspection does one notice that everything is ruled by geometry, rhythm and well thought-out order.
At night, the whole facade looks even more three-dimensional, more dramatic and the special lighting enhances the brilliance of the colors.
The same sweeping lines and intricate forms dominate the interior of the house.
Wave-shaped wood copies window frames, railings, decorative elements of doors, even peepholes and moldings.
The Batlló house in the Eixample district, on the lively shopping street Passeig de Grácia 43, was created by remodeling a house from 1877 by the architect Emilio Sala Cortese.
The reconstruction took two years and was completed in 1906.
The investor, wealthy industrialist Josep Batlló, initially insisted on demolishing the old building and building a completely new one, but ultimately agreed to Gaudí&#39;s idea of an unusual and also cheaper conversion.
However, Antoni Gaudí did not design the Casa Batlló apartment building alone.
He worked on it with the architect Josep Maria Jujol.
The decorations for the representative apartment of the real estate owner were created on his drawing board and the use of mosaics on the facade was also his idea.
However, numerous other sculptors and artists also worked on the design of the façade.
Working together on the designs for Casa Batlló was the beginning of a fruitful collaboration between Jujola and Gaudí.
Jujol also participated in the construction of Gaudí&#39;s house Casa Milá in Park Güell, which also houses other works by Antoni Gaudí.
Shortly after its completion, the house was nicknamed &quot;Bone House&quot; by local residents because of its organic shapes.
Others called it the &quot;yawning house&quot; because of the special window opening mechanism.
It is also said that the sword of Saint George, patron saint of Catalonia, is depicted at the top of the building.
But other sculptural elements also symbolize hidden religious motifs.
Gaudí designed a central heating system for the house, unique for the time, with ventilation ducts and typical chimneys.
Its 45-degree inclination seems a bit bizarre.
In his work, Gaudí consistently ignored all building regulations of the time and was by no means deterred by them.
Before construction began, he obtained the appropriate building permit from the city, but the information he provided about the planned reconstruction was so vague that the city fathers were so horrified by the result two years later that they demanded help.
Among other things, the councilors objected to the fact that the building even encroached on the public sidewalk with its pillars.
However, no changes were made, on the contrary - only fifteen days after the district&#39;s request for this, Josep Batlló applied for permission to rent the two highest floors of the house - and it was promptly granted.
The homeowner himself moved into the lower floors.
In the gallery on the 2nd floor there was a social salon, on the third floor were the bedrooms and private rooms of the apartment.
The ground floor was leased to a jewelry store.
A staircase runs through the entire six-storey building up to the roof terrace.
The fundamental elements of the renovation eliminated all right angles and straight lines and replaced them with curved and curved walls.
But Gaudí also worked with a modern concept of interconnecting spaces.
The social part can be fully connected by opening the saloon doors, allowing a larger company to chat comfortably without sacrificing a certain intimacy in more intimate conversations.
As a result of Gaudí&#39;s reconstruction, the house received not only a new facade, but also a rather unusual roof and two more floors.
Gaudí&#39;s play with light is also impressive, as are the blue and white glazed tiles that line the courtyard and the atriums.
The play of these two colors gives maximum light to all floors of the house.
In doing so, he simply made use of the principle that white reflects light better than dark colors, which on the contrary absorb sunlight.
The Casa Batlló house, which was included in the UNESCO World Heritage List in 2005, can now be visited by anyone.
On the first floor, the most spacious and magnificent apartment is open to the public.
The homeowners only decided to take this step in 2010 and this on the occasion of the 150th birthday of the famous creator.
Realizing that this was quite a lucrative business, the visits were maintained and even expanded to include other common and attic spaces, including the roof terrace.
However, the price for visiting the monument is no small matter, it is 16.50 euros, students, pensioners, groups and holders of tourist cards get a 20 percent discount.
This amount exceeds the entrance fees to other Gaudí buildings in the city.
If you want to get to know the real atmosphere of the house with its dragon towers, you should try to make friends with one of the residents and visit him at home.
The right mattress and the right bed frame? Women have different desires than men
Not the greatest bed frame, but the quality of the lying surface - i.e. the mattress and frame make a good bed.
However, these must complement each other harmoniously in order to do justice to the wishes of the specific user.
Many things play a role in the selection - the weight, height, state of health and last but not least the sex of the sleeper.
The interior is just as important, in which the mattress and frame are subordinate.
Typical example?
In a weekend home that does not have regular heating, latex mattresses are not well suited as they take much longer to &quot;warm up&quot;.
In addition, they are significantly heavier than conventional polyurethane mattresses.
And - they should be turned regularly.
If they don&#39;t have enough ventilation ducts in the core and are also lying on a solid surface, moisture accumulates: it is therefore not impossible that mold will form under it.
Of course, what you are used to also plays a role in your choice.
If you have been abroad for a long time, where very high mattresses with a soft surface are common, it will be difficult to get used to a low mattress with a hard surface.
&quot;Probably all the hockey players who have come back from the NHL have complained to me that they can no longer sleep properly here.&quot;
&quot;They simply need a soft layer of visco-foam (memory foam - a shape-memory polymer) for their sore shoulders, heels and hips.&quot;
&quot;I recommend these, among other things, to diabetic people who suffer from a disorder of the nervous system, so that they have difficulty receiving &quot;information&quot; from the joints and skin,&quot; explains Sylva Hadamcziková, who specializes in upholstered furniture.
That&#39;s why I got these mattresses with visco foam (memory foam) for many ice hockey players and other customers years ago.
&quot;Today this is no longer a problem, because such mattresses are offered by the manufacturer Tempur, the Italian company Magniflex or the Czech manufacturer Tropico, among others.&quot;
And you don&#39;t have to be a famous ice hockey player to appreciate the advantages of visco foam.
This &quot;miracle&quot; actually works quite simply.
The foam optimizes its hardness and shape according to the heat absorbed, in other words, it really clings to the warm body.
There&#39;s no pressure anywhere, you don&#39;t roll around at night like you do after a hard fight.
You just sleep a lot better.
The viscoelastic foam also offers protection against decubitus (gangrene).
When choosing the mattress size, you should always add the length of the soles of your feet to your height, i.e. approx. 21 to 34 cm.
Men and women who are around 180 cm tall need a bed that is 210 to 220 cm long.
Each of the sleepers should have at least 90 cm of lying width available, i.e. 180 cm in total.
For single beds, for example singles, 120 to 140 cm are appropriate.
For the sake of comfort and also for possible visitors.
Otherwise, the following rule of thumb applies to the ideal bed width: &quot;If you lie on your back, there should still be enough space for your slightly bent arms,&quot; advises Ing. Helena Prokopová, the guild master of upholsterers and interior decorators, who has been dealing with the problem of the healthy sleep and the ergonomics of furniture and also lectures on this topic at technical schools.
With a double bed, everyone needs their own frame and mattress, but be careful when shopping so that the mattresses are the same height.
Otherwise, there is nothing left but to mount the frames at different heights, and this is by no means possible with every bed frame.
Foam mattresses should be at least 14 cm high, mattresses with a spring skeleton 15 cm, of which at least three centimeters should be the molded layer and the fine upholstery.
&quot;You shouldn&#39;t feel the springs with your hand or when you sit down,&quot; warns Helena Prokopová.
Each mattress requires a specific type of base.
Fully upholstered beds with a mattress and pad like Siamese twins grown together have no place in the bedroom.
These mattresses cannot be aired and the cover cannot be washed, which is already commonplace these days.
And since you lose between 0.2 and 0.75 liters of sweat in a single night, it&#39;s clear that after five to seven years the mattress will slowly become a giant (and clogged sieve).
This is one of the reasons why experts reject advertising slogans that promise a lifespan of up to 25 years or even a lifetime guarantee for mattresses.
Every thing has its ifs and buts.
And therefore a practical piece of advice from retailers: with mattresses that are 120 or 140 cm wide, you should not shy away from the hygiene of the washable, removable covers, but it is advisable to use a mattress protector that can be easily removed and washed.
Even if nowadays mattress covers are usually manufactured with an all-round zip, so that when you open them you get two halves (hugely important for the washing process and the washing machine size!), the manipulation of larger mattresses, especially when done alone, often seems like an unequal fight between David and Goliath on.
Do they have a solid board in the bed instead of a grate?
Out with it!
Or at most for a bed for unwelcome guests and for a single night.
Even so, you should rather provide the plate with ventilation holes (if there aren&#39;t any in it) and use mattresses with a spring skeleton and a minimum height of 15 cm with a so-called pocket spring core and fine padding.
Polyurethane mattresses do not belong on such a base.
Latex or sandwich mattresses are suitable for non-adjustable slatted frames with 14 to 18 spring slats (possibly also combinations of latex and coconut), frames with a larger number of slats, i.e. 28 and more spring slats, with lumbar support in the lumbar area and the possibility of regulating the slat hardness.
Mattresses with a spring skeleton do not belong on adjustable slatted frames, as they do not react to the ergonomic adjustment.
In addition to adjusting the stiffness of the slats, special flexible shoulder modules are also offered.
This involves a special fastening of the spring slats, which makes it possible to press in the spring slats or even to angle them in such a way that they allow the shoulder of the sleeper to sink in at certain points.
An important thing, especially for men with broad shoulders.
There are even mattress manufacturers who have started to use soft zones for the shoulder area on &quot;men&#39;s mattresses&quot;.
We also thought of the ladies - they are treated to these soft zones in the hip area.
Point-elastic wing spring systems (Lattoflex) or grids with point-elastic contact pads with so-called multi-torsion springs are intended for the most demanding customers.
The pressure is distributed over several points, which reduces the tension.
But - if you use a bad (too big and full) pillow with the right mattress and the right frame, most of the advantages are lost again.
Here, too, a rule of thumb: the pillow should support the head, its tips should only reach the shoulders so that the shoulder muscles can relax.
A 50 x 60 cm cushion, like the ones the Scandinavians like, seems ideal.
When lying on your side, the pillow (together with the shoulder relief zone in the frame or the soft zone in the mattress) should compensate for the shoulder height.
Our modern mattresses have something in common with the straw sacks of the past (filled with hay).
Modern manufacturers are increasingly using natural materials or at least their admixtures.
The new magic word for mattresses is &quot;organic&quot;.
Instead of petroleum raw materials, natural oils - for example castor oil and soybean oil - are increasingly being used to produce polyurethane foams.
Soy is probably used by all well-known manufacturers.
&quot;In the case of mattresses, organic means that the core consists of materials of purely natural origin,&quot; explains Petr Vašíček from the company Tropico Plus.
Natural substances are also used in the manufacture of mattress covers - one of the first was aloe vera.
But you can also treat yourself to microcapsules that spread the scent of fresh forest or lavender while you sleep.
Here, too, a distinction is made between men and women.
While a &quot;cooling&quot; plant extract from birch leaves is used for men so that the mattress cover can absorb heat and cool the body, the covers for women have a &quot;warming&quot; effect.
Extracts from red peppers stimulate the blood circulation, so the weaker sex gets comfortably warm while sleeping.
And today&#39;s favourites?
Cold foam mattresses (it has larger pores with a destroyed cell structure and is therefore more breathable than standard polyurethane and also much more flexible).
The combination of the different stiffness (hardness) of cold foam and visco foam results in multi-zone mattresses that know exactly where the head, hips and heels are.
For a high-quality mattress, however, you have to shell out 7,000 crowns and more.
However, health mattresses are usually subject to lower VAT because they are considered medical aids.
Gumotex was the first Czech company to enjoy this advantage.
You can see that it is not so easy to save on the mattress and the frame.
From time to time there are special offers from manufacturers and retailers who offer two mattresses for the price of one.
For example, the Magniflex brand offers the Duofreeze mattress with a memory quilted visco-foam cover for CZK 11,990.
You get the second one for free.
It was the Tempur material that ushered in the era of open-cell, high-density viscoelastic foams at a near-cosmic pace.
No wonder, since they were developed for NASA, because the astronauts are exposed to enormous overloads during the launch.
Tempur softens when warm, and hardens again in a cool environment.
It adapts perfectly to the human body and optimally distributes body pressure.
