More and more parents want human monitoring devices to keep kids under control
Fear for their own children is growing and so more and more parents are considering monitoring them via GPS.
The system, which was originally invented to search for cars, is just as good at locating people, which would also be helpful in cases like the recent disappearance of nine-year-old Anička Janatková.
The device is currently about the size of a pack of cigarettes, but it will soon be no larger than a wristwatch.
The case of the missing Anička has terrified many people and they are looking for ways and means to better protect their children.
Even at the cost of compromising their privacy.
&quot;We try to tell everyone that this is not about spying, but an effective way to reduce the likelihood of a tragedy happening,&quot; said Petr Pilin of Macro Weil, one of the GPS suppliers -tracking devices on the Czech market.
&quot;I admit that there are cases where such devices can be misused, for example if you put it in someone&#39;s pocket without them knowing, but we haven&#39;t had a single case like this.&quot;
&quot;Most customers really buy it for security reasons,&quot; adds Pilin.
In his opinion, however, the child should always know what the &quot;box&quot; is for and how to use it in an emergency.
However, child psychologist Dana Bočková points out that if a child doesn&#39;t like wearing such a thing, they simply get rid of it.
&quot;Even very young children show great creativity when it comes to intentionally losing certain things when they don&#39;t want to be controlled.&quot;
&quot;Already the mobile phones initially aroused great expectations among the parents, but they can be switched off just as easily as these new surveillance devices,&quot; says Ms. Bočková.
In her opinion, it is also controversial whether such a facility actually helps in the event of an attack.
&quot;In planned kidnappings, the kidnappers almost always check to see if the child has any electronics that could be used to locate them.&quot;
&quot;Today it&#39;s the cell phone.&quot;
&quot;If such surveillance devices found wider use, they would seek them out as well, since their sale would certainly be accompanied by massive publicity.&quot;
&quot;In these cases, the criminals are always one step ahead of the police,&quot; says the psychologist.
However, she concedes that similar devices can certainly come in handy in the event of a sudden attack by a pedophile.
According to Roberta Čech from RC Monitoring, which provides tracking services for both automobiles and people, the existence of such a device can help even if it is destroyed immediately after the attack.
&quot;The device can be set up so that it reports the respective position at certain intervals.&quot;
&quot;Even if it were destroyed immediately, at least the last position is available to the affected person.&quot;
&quot;More expensive devices even have an inclinometer built in, which means if you fall and stay motionless, the device immediately sends an alert with your location,&quot; claims Mr. Čech.
In his opinion, similar services could also be provided by intelligent mobile phones with navigation, one only needs to import special software.
The problem with current tracking devices is that they are either matchbox-sized devices resembling fobs, or smaller cell phones.
There is always a risk of losing them.
According to Mr. Pilin from Macro Weil, devices that look like normal digital watches are currently being tested.
&quot;This has the advantage that the possible attacker does not have to recognize at all that it is a monitoring or locating device.
&quot;Or he only notices after a certain time, which gives the police a head start,&quot; he adds.
No matter in which direction the development goes - towards bracelets or tags, the same technology is always used as for vehicle tracking.
In other words, the combination of a location function using the GPS system (just like the navigation system in a car) and the function of a mobile phone that reports the current position.
The army has enough fuses to encircle the whole of the Czech Republic, but they only last two years
The Czech army has bought 445 kilometers of fuses with which to detonate explosive devices.
The year before, the Department of Defense had already delivered 224 kilometers of fuse to the army camps.
It&#39;s reassuring to know that the armed forces have made provisions for 225 years.
The only problem is the durability of the fuses - two, but at most four years.
The army bought the fuses from the joint-stock company STV Group, as for a paltry 40 million crowns.
In its justification for purchasing this massive amount of fuse, the General Staff MF DNES replied that the soldiers used about 60 kilometers of fuse annually.
