If only for the safety of the pyrotechnicians, it also keeps open the possibility of flexible purchases of more modern and therefore also more reliable fuses.
The Ministry of Defense already has huge problems liquidating tens of thousands of tons of ammunition from the days of the Warsaw Pact, when the 200,000-strong Czechoslovak People&#39;s Army was preparing for its campaign to the Rhine.
According to the pyrotechnicians contacted by MF DNES, in a few years the Czech armed forces will face the same problem of liquidating hundreds of kilometers of old fuses that they bought so &quot;cheaply&quot; today.
