Household housing costs are increasing by a few hundred every month
From January, households will not only have to reckon with higher costs for all types of energy, but also with higher water and sewage fees and for district heating and in some places rents will also increase.
From January onwards, families will have to pull several hundred crowns more out of their wallets per month than before.
Electricity will be up to 4.6 percent more expensive, gas by 2 percent and more, in some cities you will have to pay up to a tenth more for water deliveries and in some places district heating deliveries will also become more expensive.
The rise in electricity prices alone costs households a few hundred crowns more every year.
The high-voltage electricity prices were reduced by all the main suppliers, so the clear promotion of electricity generation from renewable sources, namely from photovoltaic systems, is to blame.
Gas will only become more expensive moderately, but this is exactly when people need to heat the most and have the highest consumption.
Here, too, a few hundred crowns more per year can be expected.
While electricity and gas are becoming more expensive throughout the Czech Republic, district heating prices vary from city to city.
Larger towns in particular are planning price increases.
For example, households in Pardubice and Hradec Králové will have to pay up to 50 crowns more per month for district heating from January, and families in Liberec will have to pay more than 1,000 crowns more per year.
In turn, residents of Prague are threatened with 9 percent higher water and sewage charges if the city increases infrastructure rent.
If the rent does not change, it is only 6.8 percent.
However, the price in Prague is still among the lowest compared to the whole Czech Republic.
In northern Bohemia, where prices are already among the highest, water and sewage charges are expected to rise by 7.4 percent.
Enormous rent increases are to be expected, for example, in 140,000 rental apartments, for which the so-called rent regulation will no longer apply from January.
For example, the housing company CPI Byty, which owns 2,500 apartments in Ústí nad Labem, plans to increase rents by 100 percent starting in January.
The company wants to take legal action against those who do not agree with this rent increase.
The regulated rents, which are still being paid in almost 300,000 apartments today, are likely to rise by more than 10 percent next year.
