A longer index finger than the ring finger means a lower risk of developing cancer
Men whose index finger is longer than their ring finger appear to have a lower risk of developing prostate cancer.
That&#39;s the surprising finding of a study published by the British Journal of Cancer on Wednesday.
This is said to be related to the level of the male hormone testosterone.
&#39;Our results show that relative finger length can serve as a simple test of risk of prostate cancer, particularly in men up to the age of sixty,&#39; said study co-author Ros Eeles, professor at the University of Warwick&#39;s Cancer Research Institute.
The finger could help determine which men should definitely get prostate cancer tested, especially if there are genetic risks or other risk factors, such as family history, Ms Eeles added.
In the period 1994-2009 she and her colleagues followed more than 1500 prostate cancer patients in Britain, as well as 3000 healthy men.
The index finger of the right hand was shorter than the ring finger for more than half of the participants in the study.
These men were as likely to have prostate cancer as 19 percent of men whose ring and index fingers were the same length.
However, this risk fell by 33 percent in men whose index finger was longer than the ring finger, and by as much as 87 percent in men up to sixty.
The ratio of the lengths of the two fingers mentioned, which form as early as prenatal age, apparently reflects the different levels of sex hormones to which the child was exposed in the womb.
Less testosterone equals a longer index finger.
Previous research has shown that testosterone accelerates the growth of prostate cancer.
Václav Pačes, a leading Czech geneticist and former chairman of the Academy of Sciences, told ČTK that he was vaguely aware of this study, but still didn&#39;t think the relationship between finger length and cancer risk was &quot;fully established&quot;.
