The boys leave: It&#39;s like the Tanners in many families on the island.
Experts at the economic and social research institute ESRI in Dublin predict that 100,000 Irish will probably leave the country in the near future.
They even expect 200,000 emigrants by 2015.
A heavy loss for the small country with only 4.5 million inhabitants.
If the forecasts come true, there will be a wave of emigration comparable to that which Ireland suffered in the 1980s.
After a decade of prosperity that brought great prosperity to the Irish, sadness is once again spreading.
The economic crisis unsettles the young, well-educated Irish people in particular, for whom things have only been going uphill so far.
Job losses and social decline seemed absurd in the boom years.
Everyone was needed, money was in abundance.
In the meantime, however, three out of ten women and men under thirty are unemployed.
The Irish Times abounds with letters to the editor from young expats complaining: &quot;Everything is going down the drain in Ireland.&quot;
&quot;There should be an uprising against politicians and bankers - but those who can leave and our country loses a whole generation.&quot;
&quot;The last one please turn off the light.&quot;
Law student Leanne Caulfield, president of the Irish Student Union, sees a bleak future ahead because the government is just window dressing and offering young people no future prospects.
&quot;They are reducing the minimum wage, but they have no strategy for creating new jobs,&quot; says the 20-year-old.
She watches her fellow students shimmy from one unpaid internship to the next.
Her biggest worry, she says, is having to emigrate herself in four years.
&quot;That thought is sad and depressing.&quot;
Men like Stephen McLarnon try to cast a positive light on the topic.
McLarnon organizes &quot;WorkingAbroadExpo&quot;, an exhibition that offers a full service on the subject of working abroad.
&quot;For job starters, working abroad is a great opportunity to take the first steps up the career ladder,&quot; says the manager.
Photos on his website show surfers in Australia and snowboarders in Canada.
The message is clear: working abroad is not galley service, it also brings freedom and fun.
For six months, Seán O&#39;Donovan has known how it feels to build something up somewhere else.
Because there was nothing more for the 29-year-old engineer to do in Ireland, he now works with 15 Irish colleagues on construction in Germany.
In Gelsenkirchen they are currently building a fashion house.
In January we continue to Hanover or Berlin, to the next project.
O&#39;Donovan rarely sees his home country these days, working extra shifts to pay off the loan on his house back home.
&quot;The situation is a bit crazy,&quot; he says, stepping over the threshold of his house for the first time in a long time.
&quot;I&#39;m earning money in Germany for a house in Ireland that I hardly ever stay in anymore.&quot;
He laughs a little embarrassed and walks through cold rooms.
The small house is in a fine residential area with well-tended front gardens, and large, expensive cars are parked in the driveways.
Together with a sister, O&#39;Donovan bought the house four years ago for 380,000 euros - 100 percent debt-financed.
&quot;They were crazy times, there was easy money without many questions,&quot; he says.
Is he afraid that the loan could go wrong?
O&#39;Donovan thinks for a while, then pours more hot tea and says, &quot;I don&#39;t have any kids to feed and I&#39;m young; even if things go wrong, I can start over.&quot;
The civil engineer doesn&#39;t like the wailing he hears a lot these days.
&quot;Nobody has to starve - our situation is by far not as dramatic as it used to be here on the island,&quot; he says.
&quot;Working abroad for a while isn&#39;t the worst thing that can happen - maybe that&#39;s what makes us feel Irish.&quot;
He laughs and then talks about his father, who went to England during the last great economic crisis.
&quot;After seven years he was back and life went on in Ireland, simple as that.&quot;
Cian Tanner likes this idea.
Leave the future open and just see how things are going with life somewhere else.
He already has a few years of work in London behind him and why shouldn&#39;t things go well for him and his girlfriend in New Zealand?
But there is still one thing that worries him a lot these days: the celebration of his 27th birthday on Friday in Dublin.
He fears it could turn into a farewell party.
&quot;Just don&#39;t get too emotional,&quot; he says, taking a long gulp of his beer.
&quot;Goodbye, that sounds scary.&quot;
&quot;Let&#39;s call it a walk away party, easygoing, with some friends, some drinks, some games.&quot;
The democratic routine
The democracy movement in Latin America is growing stronger, as is support for private companies.
Crime is a bigger problem than unemployment.
In many parts of the region, Brazil&#39;s influence is greater than that of the United States.
These are the findings of the Latinobarómetro survey, conducted in 18 countries and published exclusively in The Economist.
This survey has been carried out regularly since 1995 and thus shows the change of opinion in this region.
Two facts stand out in this year&#39;s survey from September and October.
Firstly, the good mood in Latin America
and second, the growing interest in democracy and its main institutions.
In numerous countries on the South American Pacific coast, the democratic movement has grown rapidly (see Table 1).
In Peru, for example, where the economy has been growing at around 6% a year since 2002, support for democracy rose from 40% in 2005 to 61% this year.
Such a trend can also be seen in Mexico, where the economy has recovered since last year&#39;s sharp slump.
Yet only half of respondents in Mexico and Brazil, the region&#39;s most populous countries, are staunch Democrats, lowering the regional average (see Chart 2).
Approximately 44% of respondents said they were satisfied with their country&#39;s democratic practice. That is as many as last year, but 25% more than in 2001 (Chart 3).
About 34% trust their country&#39;s Congress and 45% trust their government. Both values correspond to those of last year, but show a significant increase compared to 2003 (17% and 24% respectively).
A decade ago, Latin America&#39;s economic crises undermined democratic efforts.
The fact that this continued during the global economic crisis may be due to the fact that the countries of Latin America only experienced a short recession phase and quickly recovered.
In addition, the poor were cushioned by a stronger social safety net.
(The poverty rate in Latin America rose only modestly in 2009, and has fallen 32% this year, according to reports this week from the UN Economic Commission for Latin America.)
However, there are strong differences in sentiment from country to country (see Diagram 4).
Brazil&#39;s strong economy and the popularity of outgoing President Luiz Inácio Lula da Silva are reflected in a widespread progressive mentality.
This is less the case in Mexico and Central America, where the recession has been more severe and violent crime has increased.
For only the second time since the survey began, many Latin American respondents see crime as a bigger problem in their country than unemployment (see Chart 5).
Approximately 31% say either they or a family member have been a victim of a crime in the past year. However, levels have fallen from 38% last year, to their lowest level since 1995.
The increasing economic performance is reflected in the stronger support for the private and market economy: approx. 71% of those surveyed nationwide stated that the private economy is indispensable for development, in 2007 it was 56% (see Diagram 6).
About 58% said only the market economy can bring their country progress, compared to 47% last year.
Interestingly, 62% of respondents in Venezuela maintained this view (and 80% are in favor of private enterprise), despite the fact that their left-wing president, Hugo Chávez, is nationalizing many private companies.
Brazil has the greatest weight in the region, according to 19% of respondents (18% last year), followed by the United States (9%, unchanged from last year) and Venezuela (9% compared to 11% last year).
Respondents in Mexico and most of Central America, on the other hand, see the United States as the most influential country, with Venezuela assuming this role in the Dominican Republic and Nicaragua.
An election defeat
No one expected the November 28 elections in Haiti to be perfect.
But the facts far exceeded the fears of poll workers who rushed to help the troubled country.
Overcrowded ballot boxes, multiple votes cast, ballot papers in the gutter, vandalized polling stations and intimidation were just part of the problem.
Polling stations opened hours late.
Many Haitians, many of whom were displaced by January&#39;s earthquake, roamed the countryside looking for a choice.
Some eventually gave up altogether.
A dozen presidential candidates, including some suspected frontrunners, have called for the election results to be overturned over alleged fraud.
Protests, some of them violent, broke out across the country.
Nevertheless, Edmond Mulet, head of the UN mission in Haiti, described the election as &quot;quite good in many respects&quot;.
According to a cautious statement by observers from the Organization of American States and the Caribbean Community, &quot;these irregularities, serious as they are, do not necessarily invalidate the process.&quot;
In other words, the show goes on.
The electoral authority, which is said to be indebted to the unpopular outgoing President René Préval and his nominee, Jude Célestin, will announce the preliminary results on December 7.
The expected runoff election is scheduled for January.
There is still hope in the election.
The two leading opposition candidates, rap musician Michel Martelly and former first lady Mirlande Manigat, have withdrawn their initial invalidation action.
If Jude Célestin, who has little or no support from the electorate, is declared the winner of the runoff by the electoral authorities, problems could arise.
Due to the cholera epidemic and the fact that more than 1 million of the earthquake victims are still living in tents, a low turnout was feared.
On election day, many Haitians were prevented from voting due to a lack of organization.
Shortly before the start of the election, about 250,000 ID cards needed for the election had not yet been distributed.
The stakes are high.
Donor countries see legitimate, recognized government as an important step in Haiti&#39;s reconstruction.
The Haitians themselves agree.
Secretly in the middle
In the weeks following her husband&#39;s sudden death, Argentina&#39;s President, Cristina Fernández, experienced a surge of sympathy that boosted her popularity rating by 20 points to over 50%. This is the highest since she was elected in 2007.
However, whether this will get her re-elected next year depends on whether the visibly grieving Cristina Fernández is more willing to compromise than her late husband, her predecessor and political partner Néstor Kirchner.
The signs for this are not clear.
Néstor Kirchner, who continued to steer economic policy even after his wife was elected, often drew up budgets that did not fully take into account tax revenue, economic growth and inflation.
This allowed the presidential couple to spend the extra revenue as they saw fit.
On paper, the Fernández administration lost a majority in Congress last year.
But the opposition is divided, and Kirchner&#39;s death from a heart attack on October 27 led to further rifts.
Some critics of the regime from the ranks of the ruling Peronists backed Cristina Fernández.
But after chaotic sessions (with one MP slapping another in the face and others accusing the government of bribery), Congress failed to pass the 2011 budget.
&quot;I will not discuss it,&quot; said the President.
The 2010 budget now carries over into next year, giving the President even more opportunity to spend as she pleases.
The economy is running hot: it is likely to grow by up to 9% this year.
The official inflation rate is currently 11.1%, but numerous private estimates - and union wage claims - are pushing the figure to almost 30%.
Kirchner, who took office in 2003 when Argentina was rocked by economic crises, said his main goals were growth and poverty reduction, not lowering inflation.
He refused to cooperate with the IMF, bullied the private sector and purged the National Institute for Statistics and Census INDEC, which subsequently whitewashed the official inflation statistics.
Can Fernández now take a more moderate path?
She has called on the private sector and union leaders to hold talks.
And according to official statements, wage increases are to be capped at 18% next year.
The high world market prices for Argentina&#39;s agricultural products have given the economy a strong boost.
But inflation undermined the growth spurt with a major devaluation in 2002.
Possibly for this reason Cristina Fernández would like to reconnect Argentina financially with the rest of the world.
Earlier this year the government struck a deal with security holders who had opposed the country&#39;s earlier debt restructuring in 2001.
Now Fernández appears to be pushing for a deal with Paris Club lenders to whom she owes approximately $6.7 billion.
The Kirchners had always refused an IMF review, as is customary elsewhere.
But last month Economy Minister Amado Boudou announced that the fund would provide &quot;technical assistance&quot; in compiling a new national consumer price index. It looks like this is the first step in cleaning up the INDEC.
It is not known whether Fernández will be politically active after the end of her term without the support of her husband.
If so, it needs the support of the middle class, most of whom are fed up with Kirchnerism.
By the time the Argentines return from their summer vacation in March, the wave of sympathy she received will have ebbed.
If she wants to win another election, she must choose between quietly overturning many of her husband&#39;s political decisions.
Weak applause for China
Taiwan&#39;s voters are slowly moving towards closer ties with the mainland.
What does Taiwan think of its big brother across the straits?
On November 27, more than 7.5 million voters, 70% of all eligible voters, turned out to elect mayors and councilors in the five boroughs. This is taken as a broad assessment of President Ma Ying-jeou.
Having developed pioneering business relationships, including a partial free trade agreement, Ma has become a symbol of mainland relations himself. His policies changed relations with mainland China for the first time since 1949.
Ma passed the exam, but just barely.
Although his Kuomintang Party (KMT) provided three of the five mayors, it did not get a majority of votes.
Instead, the Democratic Progressive Party (DPP), which advocates greater independence for Taiwan, received almost 50% of the vote, while the KMT received 45%.
In a presidential election, this would have meant problems for Ma.
Since his election two years ago, his party&#39;s share of the vote has fallen by around 8%.
For the first time, the DPP even entered the city councils together with the KMT.
During the election, the usual incidents in Taiwan such as truck convoys with rioters, flag-waving mass processions and scantily clad dancers took place.
There was even the obligatory mysterious attempted murder.
Sean Lien, son of Lien Chan and honorary chairman of the KMT, gave a speech on the eve of the election for a KMT candidate,
when a man in the crowd shot him in the face. Lien was wounded and a bystander killed.
Bizarrely, it&#39;s not clear if the shooter was trying to kill Lien or settle a dispute with the candidate.
Regardless, according to Tsai Ing-wen, leader of the DPP, the attack marred the election and cast the DPP in a bad light, giving the KMT more votes.
China may have been the campaign&#39;s biggest winner.
Remarkably, relations with the mainland were not discussed.
Instead, the candidates debated public housing plans and job creation.
The Taiwanese love their virtual independence and reject China&#39;s military threat.
For this reason, the KMT does not like to prioritize its relations with the Beijing government.
This time, however, the DPP also avoided stoking anti-Chinese sentiment too much.
She was reacting to the new awareness that Taiwan&#39;s economy cannot survive without China.
For his part, Ma wants confirmation that the majority of Taiwanese support his China policy.
The Beijing government will continue to pursue its strategy of luring Taiwan back into the community with economic incentives.
China immediately sent a negotiator to Taipei to prepare a summit on investment security and medical cooperation.
Certainly, it also wants political integration. But first things first.
It prefers to wait until after the 2012 presidential election.
The DPP has now reinvented itself.
Two years ago it was severely weakened: former party leader Chen Shui-bian was in prison for corruption.
During his presidency from 2000 to 2008, he vehemently advocated absolute independence.
But under Tai&#39;s reign, a new generation of moderate politicians has emerged and the DPP is fighting for the votes of professionals and youth.
Tsai was well received as the DPP&#39;s presidential candidate, as was Su Tseng-chang under Chen.
Her party is now doing everything it can to show that it, too, is capable of building close ties with Beijing.
Tsai is planning a think tank as a point of contact between the DPP and China. However, this requires unprejudiced discussions.
Tsai publicly stated that her party offers a &quot;trustworthy alternative&quot; to Ma&#39;s hasty rapprochement with China.
Chen seems very upset about this move.
From his cell, he said the DPP candidates would have done better to insist on Taiwan&#39;s independence.
He even asked the pragmatist Su to give up the presidential candidacy.
Even without Chen&#39;s interference, the DPP is struggling to choose its possible candidate.
The KMT will have to undergo its own self-analysis.
Ma&#39;s scores are poor despite rapid economic growth; the KMT candidates wanted to campaign without him.
The main reasons for his unpopularity seem to be unemployment and the widening gap between rich and poor.
According to a KMT spokesman, he will reorganize his cabinet and local institutions.
The strong stance of the DPP suggests that Taiwan&#39;s support for a rapprochement is limited.
At the same time, most Taiwanese view economic cooperation with China as inevitable.
According to Antonio Chiang, a prominent columnist, &quot;there is already no turning back&quot;.
Grammy nominations: Jazz singer Esperanza Spalding was surprisingly awarded in the Newcomer of the Year category
If you perform at the request of a president, people will take notice.
President Obama himself asked Esperanza Spalding to perform at the 2009 Nobel Prize ceremony. Now the 26-year-old jazz bassist and singer has surprisingly been nominated for this year&#39;s Grammy in the Newcomer of the Year category.
Given that Spalding has already been a celebrated star on the jazz scene since her 2008 album Esperanza, the nomination seems a bit unusual. But it conforms to Grammy rules, according to which an artist can only have released a maximum of three albums before the release of the album that made them known to the general public.
Her ambitious 2010 album Chamber Music Society is certainly a step forward. And with her lilting voice and keen flair for pop, funk and Latin music, Spalding can easily be compared to Norah Jones 2003, whose huge success in 2003 as a jazz performer in this category comes closest to Spalding&#39;s nomination.
The album &quot;Historicity&quot; by the Vijay Iyer Trio was also nominated in the instrumental albums category. This made this critics&#39; darling a smash hit.
Iyer&#39;s contenders include veteran saxophonist James Moody&#39;s &quot;Moody 4B&quot; and keyboardist John Beasley&#39;s &quot;Positootly&quot;.
Trombone Shorty, a tough New Orleans favorite and frequent guest on HBO&#39;s &quot;Treme,&quot; was recognized in the contemporary jazz category, which tends to feature albums by Stanley Clarke, John McLoughlin and Jeff Lorber.
Wild steampunk musician Darcy James Argue&#39;s Secret Societ received well-deserved attention in the Large Group category. He goes up against the Billy Childs ensemble with his chamber jazz and the adventurous Dave Holland and his octet, whose life album &quot;Pathways&quot; is a good example of a bassist as a democratic bandleader.
Grammy Nominations: Michael Daugherty, Steve Mackey lead in Classic categories
The classical nominations for the 53rd Grammy Awards contain a colorful mix of musicians and composers from all over the world.
Topping the list are Michael Daugherty&#39;s &quot;Deux Ex Machina&quot; for piano and orchestra in five voices, and Steve Mackey&#39;s &quot;Dreamhouse&quot;, an eclectic orchestral work in three voices.
