Arsenic-resistant microbe could enable new life forms on Earth or elsewhere
The discovery of an alien species of bacteria that can live on arsenic, among other things, opens up new possibilities for new life forms on Earth and elsewhere.
Although scientists discovered this unusual bacterium here on Earth, they believe it is a sign that life is possible without the elements previously thought essential to life.
&quot;This organism has two options.&quot;
&quot;It needs either phosphorus or arsenic to grow.&quot;
&quot;That makes it very special, even though it&#39;s almost a kind of &#39;alien&#39; life form,&quot; said Paul CW Davies of Arizona State University and co-author of the report, which appears in Thursday&#39;s online edition of the journal Science.
So far, six main elements have been considered essential to life - carbon, hydrogen, nitrogen, oxygen, phosphorus and sulphur.
However, as the scientists found out, the bacterium in Mono Lake, California, continues to grow even when it replaces phosphorus with arsenic.
&quot;It makes you wonder what else is possible,&quot; said report co-author Ariel D. Anbar of Arizona State University.
The discovery is an important step in the search for extraterrestrial life, as scientists need to recognize life and its forms, Anbar said.
The study looks at microbes found on Earth.
The announcement of a press conference that did not provide details of the discovery sparked widespread speculation online that the report could be about the discovery of extraterrestrial life.
This is not the case.
The discovery &quot;shows that in other planetary systems, organisms can use other elements to initiate biochemical processes, and that the &#39;standard elements&#39; that we believe are absolutely necessary for life are not necessarily fixed,&quot; said Charles Cockell, professor at the Planetary and Space Sciences Research Institute at the Open University of Milton Keynes in the UK.
Cockel was not part of the research team.
&#39;This work is first because it shows that one element can be substituted for another in fundamental biochemical processes and structures,&#39; added Cockell.
This discovery was not accidental.
Felisa Wolfe-Simon of NASA&#39;s Astrobiology Institute, who led the study, chose Mono Lake because of its high arsenic content.
Since arsenic and phosphorus are chemically similar, she hypothesized that exposure to both microbes might be able to substitute one element for the other.
&quot;The toxicity of arsenic is mainly due to the fact that it behaves chemically in a similar way to phosphorus.&quot;
&quot;This makes it difficult for organisms to distinguish one element from another.&quot;
&quot;But the difference is so big that arsenic works differently than phosphorus. It gets into our biochemical system, where it basically smears everything,&quot; explains Anbar.
The researchers exposed the bacterium GFAJ-1 to an increasing concentration of arsenic. It adapted and grew.
While the microbe grows better in phosphorus, its ability to survive in arsenic shows that an arsenic-based life-form can occur naturally, either on Earth or on another planet or moon where arsenic is more abundant.
According to Jamie S. Foster, associate professor of microbiology at the University of Florida, the idea that arsenic can be substituted for phosphorus is not new. But so far there hasn&#39;t been a working example.
Arsenic was more common in the early Earth years, she says, so scientists have assumed that early life forms used it.
&quot;This gives reason to believe that life may have evolved differently than it did in the early geological era,&quot; said Forster, who was not a member of Wolfe-Simon&#39;s research team.
The research was supported by NASA, the Department of Energy and the National Health Authorities.
Remaining stolen show dogs found in Compton
The remaining two of the four show dogs stolen from outside a Bellflower motel were found, the Los Angeles County Sheriff said Thursday.
The four show dogs -- two Akitas and two Pembroke Welsh Corgis -- disappeared Tuesday when strangers stole the 2006 Chevrolet Express van in which the animals were being housed outside a Bellflower Motel 6 at night, authorities said.
Two of the dogs were spotted Wednesday afternoon, and the final two were spotted Wednesday night, said Steve Whitmore, a spokesman for the Los Angeles County Sheriff&#39;s Department.
&quot;The good news is the dogs are doing well,&quot; said Whitmore.
&quot;They are in good condition.&quot;
&quot;They have been returned to their rightful owners.&quot;
Whitmore did not provide specific information about the location of the dogs or the circumstances that led to their discovery.
&quot;The investigation is still ongoing.&quot;
&quot;We don&#39;t want to say more about that,&quot; explains Whitmore.
&quot;We&#39;re following some leads.&quot;
The dog&#39;s owners, Kristina Rickard and David Peek, were not available for information Thursday.
They received their two dogs at a county animal shelter in Downey on Wednesday afternoon.
Sheriff&#39;s officials found the van and the two dogs in separate locations in Compton.
The Akitas -- Trace, a 3-year-old male, and Didi, a 10-month-old female -- were unharmed, officials said.
But the corgis Bunny and Peter, who wanted to present Rickard and Peek at the competition this week on behalf of their Japanese owners, remained missing until Wednesday evening.
Peek and Rickard, who live in Redding, were in town this weekend for the AKC/Eukanuba National Championship in Long Beach, where Trace was scheduled to compete.
As Peek told the Times Wednesday, the other dogs were scheduled to compete in other competitions in the days leading up to the AKC/Eukanuba show.
Southern California is a stop on the couple&#39;s nearly month-long tour from dog show to dog show.
On Monday evening, Peek and Rickard checked into the motel.
They often stay in motels and park their van in front of their room window.
They took three other dogs -- a boxer puppy, a Parson Russell Terrier, and a Brittany -- to their motel room.
The thick-skinned Akitas and Corgis stayed in the van because it was cooler there.
They left the window ajar so the dogs could get some fresh air.
Peek and Rickard reported their car stolen at 6:00 a.m. Tuesday.
Peek promised a finder&#39;s fee to anyone who could provide information about the corgis. The animals were implanted with microchips for identification.
On Thursday it was not yet clear whether a finder&#39;s fee would be paid.
The lion roars again after court approval of MGM restructuring
After 18 months of turbulence and uncertainty, MGM finally got the green light to start over.
A New York bankruptcy judge on Thursday officially approved the &quot;prepared&quot; lender plan to pay down $5 billion in debt and pave the way for the 86-year-old entertainment company to launch new movies and TV shows.
According to statements made Thursday, the plan complies with US bankruptcy law requirements, leaving nothing standing in the way of MGM&#39;s restart under the direction of Gary Barber and Roger Birnbaum, founders of Spyglass Entertainment. Barber and Birnbaum will lead the somewhat slimmed-down studio as general managers.
The number of employees is reduced from over 400 to around 320.
