Several governments have tried to polish the image of China&#39;s city inspectors.
In one city, all new applicants must have a college degree.
Guangdong Province introduced a bright blue uniform instead of the grey-green one.
Wuhan, in central China, replaced violence with stares: in 2009, 50 officers reportedly circled an improperly set up food truck and stared at the operator, who half an hour later packed up and left the place.
Xindu, a district in Chengdu with 680,000 inhabitants, would like to fundamentally change its image.
Since 2003, 13 women have reinforced the municipal police patrols. They were specifically chosen for their looks, good shape and youth.
They are intended to give the rough-hewn police force a softer, more feminine aspect.
Unfortunately, even Scarlett Johansson would hardly succeed in improving the poor image that the Chinese have of these city commandos.
Rightly so, say the critics.
Unlike the police, these officers may enforce city laws only through fines or other administrative penalties.
