A violent video game downloadable from the Internet shows Chinese-trained officers attacking street vendors.
&quot;Chengguan scares the government,&quot; the national newspaper China Daily lamented last year, following further controversy over the tactics.
The newspaper called for a &quot;really thorough cleanup.&quot;
Skeptics consider the current approach to be clearly inadequate.
In October, when the district advertised for eight female recruits, an editorial in the Beijing Evening News questioned whether the women had real jobs or were just a visual distraction.
Probably both.
According to the job advertisement, women between the ages of 18 and 22 with a good figure and &quot;harmonious facial features&quot; were wanted.
They should be above average height - over 1.5m or 5 feet, 2 1/2 inches.
The employment relationship ends when the employee reaches the age of 26.
According to officials, the job is too physically demanding for women over 25.
&quot;The most important thing is their image,&quot; an unnamed district official told the quasi-government website Rednet.com.
&quot;Whether the candidates get the job depends first on their physical appearance, such as height, weight, facial features, etc.&quot;
