&quot;Female chengguan are like flower vases,&quot; he said, adding, &quot;but beyond that, they have other duties.&quot;
Zheng Lihua, deputy chief of the district municipal government, does not agree with this description,
admitted, however, that size specifications in job advertisements for both sexes are not uncommon in China.
The same goes for even facial features.
Whether that equates to good looks is a matter of debate in China.
But people with disabilities or physical disfigurements do not need to apply.
&quot;Unfortunately, we don&#39;t need lame people or hunchbacks here,&quot; said Mr. Zheng.
&quot;Your image would not be good.&quot;
Liu Yi, who patrols Baoguang Square near a monastery, is 22, has apple cheeks and a shapely mouth.
She didn&#39;t find it sexist that so much emphasis was placed on her appearance.
&quot;Do you think I look sexy in this uniform?&quot; she asks with an ironic look.
Her dimpled colleague, 21-year-old Xu Yang, comments, &quot;Our job is to represent the city&#39;s image.&quot;
According to them, they have no regrets about the brief hiring as they have more ambitious career plans than simply chasing traders through the streets to prevent them from doing business.
