Can politeness connect what divides?
Little civility erupted in Washington this week after a campaign of swear words and negativity.
Is it the omen of genuine bipartisan cooperation or a moment of illusion before rushing back to the factional struggle in the capital?
Tuesday&#39;s meeting between President Obama and congressional leaders failed to break the big questions to be dealt with during the so-called &quot;lame duck session&quot; at the end of a non-decision-making administration had.
From what is heard, it was neither a polite discussion between two different sides, nor an observance of their shared responsibility to govern, but rather an empty episode of partisan point-scoring.
The public meeting of the President&#39;s deficit commission on Wednesday was also civilized, despite political differences that persist among members.
It seems clear that close interaction over a period of months breeds a mutual respect that obscures the ideological gulf that continues to separate members.
That&#39;s hardly enough to claim that a new era of cooperation has dawned.
Both sides are now in a testing phase - one urging the other to show signs of cooperation and compromise while trying to gauge the limits of public opinion and the patience of voters after renewed factional warfare.
As a result, Tuesday&#39;s meeting itself, and its assessment by participants, was limited to a minimum of demands or recriminations.
The philosophical differences between Obama and the Republicans are too great and too deep to expect a rapid change in the atmosphere that has prevailed over the past two years.
Whether it&#39;s about taxes, donations, health or entitlements, the two sides are miles apart.
Last but not least, the November elections put Washington in a mild mood, at least for a short time.
&quot;There&#39;s no question the tone has changed,&quot; said Pete Wehner, a Bush administration official who now works for the Ethics and Public Policy Center.
&quot;It&#39;s inevitable after elections.
Elections awaken partisan passions that die out again.
And that&#39;s good.&quot;
On some issues, particularly those on the agenda of the lame duck session, Republicans and Democrats have little choice but to find a solution.&quot;
Bush&#39;s tax cuts end at the end of the year, and no one supports that.
Both sides want to find a way to preserve some or all, whether temporarily or permanently.
A compromise on increased unemployment benefits is also likely, if only because Republicans can&#39;t afford to be believed to favor tax cuts for the wealthy while withholding support for unemployed workers.
After Tuesday&#39;s meeting at the White House, optimism has grown that agreement on these issues can be reached during the lame duck session and the New START treaty can be ratified at the same time.
But William Glaston of the Brookings Institution warns that successful cooperation on urgent issues of the &#39;lame duck session&#39; may not necessarily result in lasting cooperation between the parties when the new 112th Congress convenes in January.
Instead, he says, a period of disagreement is more likely, perhaps even inevitable.
&quot;After the things that need to be done are done, that short-term psychology will turn into confrontation,&quot; he said.
Wehner is also skeptical - and this skepticism is shared by many - that politeness leads to true cooperation.
&quot;I see a lot of what&#39;s happening from now through 2012 as prelims, or shadow boxing, for the main event of 2012,&quot; he said.
The reasons for this have a lot to do with the makeup of the new Republican majority in the White House and the Tea Party voters who helped educate them.
However concerned Republican leaders may be about playing too big a game, they know they must try to live up to their promises to cut government spending and overturn health care reform.
These party lines are already evident in the initial reactions to the Deficit Commission&#39;s recommendations, which include tax reform and some tax increases, as well as raising the retirement age and cutting government spending.
Vice Chairmen Alan Simpson and Erskine Bowles have taken on one of the toughest jobs in Washington and, by their own admission, have pushed so hard to put the deficit issue on the public agenda that it can no longer be ignored.
But they need 14 of the 18 votes on the commission to make their plan an official recommendation, and they&#39;re struggling to get anywhere near that number.
Most opposition is found within the body&#39;s elected officials, as there is little room or sympathy for compromise on financial issues, at least today.
Galston predicts two phases in the struggle between the White House and Republicans in Congress.
The first battle will come next year in the form of partisan clashes as Republicans challenge Obama over the state budget, taxes and health care system, followed later by a period of greater bipartisan cooperation.
What will lead to this change?
The public opinion.
Evidence shows that, despite the partiality of the current election, the majority of Americans still want the two parties to work together.
When confrontation leads to an impasse, as happened in 1995, both parties need to be careful about the public reaction.
Whoever is doomed to lose will have to change course and find compromise.
That may indeed be an optimistic view.
Partisanship and polarization are greater today than they were in the mid-1990s, and there appears to be a greater ideological divide between Obama and Congressional Republicans than between President Bill Clinton and Republicans in his day.
At the same time, activists from both parties see 2010 as a mere prelude to a far more far-reaching election in 2012.
In that light, the courtesy on display this week may be welcomed by many Americans.
But it will take far more effort on both sides to find common ground on the issues that still separate the two.
