On the other hand, according to family records, the founder of the service group demands the right to use 51% of the capital.
That is the real background to the matter the judge is to decide at the challenge hearing, which has not yet been set a date.
Red Bull wins F1 with a secret weapon from Siemens
The cars are improved with real-time software.
Ever since Red Bull entered the world of Formula 1 in 2004, their history in this exquisite universe of speed has been one of surprises and successes.
Initially no one paid any attention to the newcomer and despite his rapid rise over the past few seasons, everyone was counting on Fernando Alonso&#39;s Ferrari to win in the final sprint last November.
Without wanting to belittle the skills of the German pilot and world champion Sebastian Vettel or the power of the Renault engine, the &quot;secret weapon&quot; that the multinational Siemens put into Red Bull&#39;s hands and thus created a winning team has become a legend.
In reality, it is a powerful software for simulating processes that the German company launched in 2007 for purposes not related to car racing.
This informatics program, called PLM, has been used for the development of assembly chains in factories around the world, power plants and high-precision instruments.
The aim is to faithfully reproduce or simulate a product or process before it is actually built, to avoid errors and unnecessary costs.
PLM has facilitated the development of Canon&#39;s cameras, Sukhoi&#39;s airplanes and Nissan&#39;s most famous commercial vehicles.
Siegfried Russwurm, head of the industrial department at Siemens, explains that with the use of this software at the Red Bull Formula 1 factory, &quot;in a few hours, almost in real time&quot;, the changes and improvements detected during the races and tests can design and execute.
Russwurm explains that in 1992 there were an average of ten technicians working in the racing teams, who could introduce at most three or four improvements in one season.
Today, 180 highly qualified young people are employed in Red Bull&#39;s team. Using high-performance EDP systems, they carry out analyzes and all sorts of modifications to the racing cars.
The Siemens manager explained that the PLM software is able to analyze and improve all components of Red Bull&#39;s racing cars, with the exception of the engine, for which Renault claims sole responsibility.
The materials, the fuel, the aerodynamics and the safety elements are changed.
Thanks to advanced production facilities and high-tech autoclaves, the changes can be transferred from the virtual reality of the simulator to reality in less than 24 hours.
The only limit to this crazy technical perfectionism is the $40 million that a Formula 1 team can spend on its races in one season.
Red Bull has set up its high-tech factory for the development and manufacture of its racing cars in a location 50 kilometers from London.
These are two buildings where visits - especially by journalists - are very limited.
Everything that happens there is top secret.
The workforce consists of 580 people, including the two pilots, World Champion Vettel and Mark Webber.
But Red Bull&#39;s true Formula 1 hero is undoubtedly the latest world champion, Sebastian Vetell.
Behind the enormous technological resources that the energy drink manufacturer puts at the service of its participation on the circuits, there are other protagonists whose support is invaluable and whose notoriety is nil.
The plant&#39;s chief technology officer, Steve Nevey, points out that five years ago it was still possible to say that advances in racing car R&amp;D contributed 50 percent to victory and the drivers were responsible for the rest.
Today the share values have changed. Technology accounts for 85 percent of success, while pilot contribution is estimated at 15 percent.
Nevey acknowledges that Vettel and Webber can never be replaced by computing because they &quot;are unpredictable gladiators&quot;.
