Sabadell wants to &#39;steal&#39; its rival a million customers in three years
Banco Sabadell&#39;s executive director Jaime Guardiola is more optimistic than other executives. He believes that 2001 will be a tough year for the banks, but initially dismisses a new liquidity crisis and predicts the end of the debt war.
Nonetheless, he foresees a collapse in interest rate spreads, which banks are attempting to offset by increasing fees and loan prices.
Sabadell expects to capture 1 million retail customers in three years -- a league to come.
Sabadell has found the way to make the most of the next three years, surviving in a very complicated economic environment.
In 2011, the bank will introduce a new three-year master plan.
The goal is not only to survive without recourse to FROB public aid, but also to increase market share by one million retail customers - 700,000 if you subtract the customers the bank will lose. This is the big challenge facing this bank, because until now it has paid more attention to its commercial customers than to its private customers.
This year she added 250,000 private customers and 50,000 companies.
Their market share for private customers is 3.5 percent, while business customers make up more than 10 percent.
Another principle of the 2011-2013 business plan is to increase productivity, ie austerity, cost reduction. She will present the challenges that the bank is facing with this together with the annual report.
Only a few banks dare to set and publish targets in these difficult times, as the financial crisis has thrown all the plans of the banks all over the world into disarray.
This year Sabadell will complete its Optima roadmap set out four years ago. This was initially designed for three years, but due to the market situation it was extended by one financial year.
The customers who will leave the savings banks are the main target of the bank.
At a breakfast organized by APIE, Guardiola stressed that 2011 would be a &quot;difficult&quot; year &quot;with great scope&quot;.
The manager assumes that Spain would only &quot;slowly&quot; emerge from the crisis.
In addition, it would be &quot;very difficult&quot; to &quot;create work&quot; in two or three years - essential for the survival of the banks.
Even as he expects the liabilities war - which penalizes interest margins - to abate, the risk premium banks and thrifts must pay on their issues to maintain liquidity is already being passed on to the price of credit to compensate for shrinking profit margins .
&quot;The liquidity and funding issues are structural and they will put pressure on credit.&quot;
&quot;We haven&#39;t turned off the tap, but the interest rate differentials are very high,&quot; admitted Guardiola.
On Thursday, Banesto issued an order to its branch network to limit long-term lending and increase interest rate differentials (see Cinco Días of November 22 and 27).
The manager also admitted the banks&#39; current strategy is to &quot;increase fees&quot;, albeit &quot;within a competitive framework&quot;.
Sabadell&#39;s roadmap is based on organic growth, although, as always, the group does not rule out corporate deals.
It is not for nothing that he affirms that &quot;larger companies are necessary&quot; in Spain.
&quot;Everything will change in the coming year,&quot; he assures.
He emphasizes that the need for capital is &quot;growing enormously&quot; at the moment and does not rule out that some Spanish financial institutions will slip into the red.
He thinks the FROB can replace the money market for capital increases.
After assuring that Sabadell could survive a temporary market shutdown, he refutes the argument of some bankers who are already predicting a new liquidity crisis.
He emphasizes that nothing can be circulated, but unlike what happened in June, short-term financing can be obtained through repurchase agreements, thereby cushioning the crisis.
