Zapatero and the red line of Germany
Berlin decided to keep the euro, but at the same time set conditions for the entire European Union.
Tensions in the markets have prompted a dual response from the government.
On the one hand, José Luis Rodríguez Zapatero has presented new adjustment measures, ranging from tax breaks for small and micro-enterprises, the regulation of temporary work agencies or the abolition of the 426 euro support for the unemployed who do not receive unemployment benefits, to the privatization of 49 percent of AENA, the administration of Barajas and El Prat airports and 30 percent of the state lottery.
On the other hand, Deputy Prime Minister Elena Salgado, with the help of former Prime Minister Felipe González, supports the criticism of Chancellor Angela Merkel as responsible for provoking the current crisis.
How are these processes to be understood?
It is anticipated that Merkel&#39;s position is not a mistake in her public relations work.
On the contrary, it is a new round in the difficult process of redefining the euro.
In doing so, Germany adopts a fundamentally new perspective on shaping our future that clashes with maintaining the long-established traditions of most of its partners.
In view of the resistance in Europe, people in Germany are beginning to speculate about three possible ways out of the crisis.
The first: A strong euro with Germany, Austria, the Netherlands and other countries, while the south would have to leave the euro area.
The second: the reintroduction of the Deutsche Mark - although that sounds more like science fiction at the moment - supported by a large part of public opinion, about 50 percent of the population.
The Third: A Reshaping of the Euro According to German Proposals. That means: more macroeconomic control; strict housekeeping; penalizing countries that break the rules; possibly the default of some countries and the extension of the costs of potential adjustment measures to the private sector.
The German position is clear and has been emerging for some time. So now there are no excuses.
First in 2009, when both the IMF and the European Commission were stimulating deficits and the German government pulled up a constitutional reform to prevent this from 2016 onwards.
That was the first sign of a divergence between what Germany saw as necessary (strict tax plans and stable public finances) and the practices of its European partners, including France.
The Central European country set the second sign when Merkel painfully postponed the decision to save Greece.
It was heavily criticized at the time. But the fact is that the political consensus in Germany, public and published opinion were absolutely against a rescue of Greece.
Finally, in the last few days of October, Merkel came out again with a clear position. She calls for a reform of the European Union&#39;s agreements to allow a country to be rescued while requiring private lenders to bear part of the cost.
This position was construed as anti-European as it fueled the Irish Crisis and all that followed.
But her suggestion, albeit a little sweetened, was accepted. In the coming months we will be involved in the reform of the European Union, which should make these measures possible from 2013.
Germany has drawn a red line that it does not intend to cross.
It tells everyone that, even if unpopular measures have to be taken now, the old way of working for the euro will no longer exist from that date.
2013 will be the birth year of a new currency area in which violating countries will be severely penalized, can be forced to declare bankruptcy and in which case the private sector will have to bear part of the cost.
Germany is showing us that we need to embark on a tough growth path, with high savings and investment rates, moderation in consumption, improvements in productivity and competitiveness, and positive external balances.
The other alternative, based on debt and construction with huge gaps in the balance of payments, such as that spearheaded by Spain in boom times, will simply not be accepted.
The offer is clear.
And we would do badly not to understand it.
It&#39;s not just about reducing the national deficit to three percent by 2013.
The demands are much tougher.
And the worst thing we could do under these conditions is cheat ourselves.
I hope that the current turbulence will give way to more calm.
And that we will use the opportunities that are offered to us by spring 2013.
It seems that Zapatero understood this as well, and his double announcement (the promised reforms after last Saturday&#39;s meeting with big business and the announcement of new measures yesterday) indicates that despite the criticism of Merkel, the hypothesis that order to create in-house has paved its way.
But the red line drawn by Germany is there and it doesn&#39;t look like anything will change.
Among the possibilities under consideration, one that cannot be ruled out is that we would have to leave the euro area, which is crammed with less serious countries.
In that case, Germany could still tell us it warned us.
Sport and evasion of the rules
Tricks like those of Alonso and Ramos in the game against Ajax show inventiveness, but not the will to avoid a sanction.
The exclusion allegedly instigated by two Real Madrid players (Xabi Alonso and Sergio Ramos) in the November 23 match against Ajax in the Champions League led to much ink being spilled over whether or not it was an unsportsmanlike act acted and whether both players should possibly be sanctioned by UEFA.
As is well known, a few minutes before the end of the game (their team had already clearly won) the two players lost time and played several fouls to get the referee to show them the second yellow card.
In this way, and since Real Madrid would lead their group, the two players will meet the mandatory sanction in the next league game against Auxerre and thus enter the next phase of the game without tickets.
Eventually, the UEFA Disciplinary Committee fined the club&#39;s coach, José Mourinho, with two games and the players involved with different amounts of money.
Provoking a yellow card in these or similar circumstances is not a new practice, it is rather common in the world of football.
It&#39;s so widespread that it&#39;s part of the ethos - the unwritten rules that are followed in the sport.
Part of the debate that has ensued around the case presented stems from the fact that a team from Real Madrid football club (which promotes nobility and honor in its anthem and has on other occasions punished its players for similar incidents) starred in it, and from the dramatization by it Mourinho, who added one more episode to his long history as a theatrical and provocative technician.
In any case, the debate revolves around whether this behavior, which is not expressly prohibited by the statutes, is contrary to the principles of sport, that is, whether these acts constitute circumvention of the rules. In fact, this approach adheres to the statutes of the sport, but seems to circumvent its spirit.
In this matter, the damage done to sportsmanship should be examined.
Sportsmanship defends the physical integrity of opponents, an aspect that was not compromised by these actions because it was not an aggressive game.
Another aspect of clean play is to avoid allowing the offending players to take undue advantage of the opposing team. That didn&#39;t happen either.
The paradox of the action of the Real Madrid players is that it is not what we usually understand by cheating or circumventing the rules, because the circumvention of the rule was not done secretly to avoid a sanction, but it should be as obvious as possible , to be penalized by the referee.
The players waited and happily accepted the sanction.
Another question is what kind of benefit the offenders got from the intentional fouls.
It should be emphasized here that the rival was not put in a less favorable position, nor was any advantage demanded for the game being played, since the obvious result of this action was that one&#39;s team had to continue playing with fewer players.
It&#39;s also not a useful strategy for the next game because the club doesn&#39;t have those players.
The benefit, obviously, is that players start the next phase of the Champions League with no cards that could threaten their participation in a future game.
But it&#39;s a long-term benefit, uncertain to some degree, as the team could also be eliminated at some point. Also, with this practice, players are penalized and move into the second card cycle, where they are eliminated due to card accumulation with one card fewer than in the first cycle.
It is therefore not so clear whether this is really an advantage.
Ultimately, such practices do not go against the spirit of sportsmanship, which includes making strategic decisions to get the most out of the regulations.
In this case, the players didn&#39;t want to circumvent a sanction (this would actually be a clear case of circumvention), they rather wanted to choose when to undergo it.
They made a strategic decision without dodging or escaping punishment.
Although the line between inventiveness and the regulatory environment is blurred, I believe that this is a clear case of inventiveness.
I have the impression that the polemic arose as a result of two factors: because it was about two self-exclusions and because of the way in which the rules were provoked.
The harm done to the principles of sport by these acts is less ethical than aesthetic.
Promotion campaign to attract customers for group Christmas dinners in Barcelona
The dictatorship of the calendar is dropping an avalanche of reservations on December 16th and 17th this year.
Employee self-sponsored celebrations are spreading. You don&#39;t want to spend more than 20 to 30 euros.
Like the turrón and the Christmas lottery, the run-up to Christmas also sees the return of group dinners that breathe new life into Barcelona&#39;s hospitality and leisure industries. But as a result of the economic crisis, they are launching a price offensive in order to capture the customer segment that represents the great majority: almost everyone would like to spend between 20 and 30 euros for lunch or dinner, confirm the surveyed entrepreneurs and associations.
To add a bit of complexity to the accounting, the calendar (New Year&#39;s Eve falls on a Friday) has dropped all orders into the week of December 13, resulting in an avalanche of dinner reservations on two peak days (the 16th and 17th). ) and almost no orders in the week before.
Since 2008, when the bad times started, many companies have stopped group dinners for budget reasons.
In order not to have to do without this tradition, many employees pay for it out of their own pockets.
Whatever the state of the economy, rock-bottom prices are required, confirms the chairman of the Barcelona Catering Council, Gaietà Farràs.
The representative of the umbrella organization does not yet dare to predict what the holidays will be like this month.
&quot;People think twice before making a reservation.&quot;
&quot;They want to go out, but they&#39;re very price conscious,&quot; he says.
Business will be good for those &quot;who offer quality at good prices with good service,&quot; he adds, reminding us that customers save in times of crisis, which is why prices around 25 euros are the most popular.
A survey of various centrally located restaurants reveals that the evening of December 17th causes the suppliers to collapse.
The Soteras group says demand is booming this Friday with intentions to spend less than 30 euros. The group has adapted its menus to the economic situation with complete offers between 25 and 35 euros.
For another leading group, Andilana, which has 16 inns in the city (Hostal de la Rita, Market, La Fonda and others), the peculiarity of the calendar has led to early bookings, even from early November.
&quot;We have done the impossible to maintain last year&#39;s prices with menus for all tastes ranging from 19.95 to 30 euros,&quot; he explains.
AN Grup, which manages El Mussol, Attic, QuQu and a total of 23 establishments, is not losing optimism after the revenues have been booming again since the second quarter and the prospects for the Christmas business are good, albeit concentrated in a few days.
Group sources highlight that the 18th will also be an overactive day with groups of friends celebrating the run-up to Christmas.
A Christmas menu for 30 euros or more has been added to the six group menus as a price hit. One gets the impression that customers are willing to spend 10 percent more than last year and in return want more details, such as cava.
Green sprouts can also be seen in some companies, which is why the employees are invited back. This gives the impression that group meals are on the rise again.
On the part of the Fecasarm umbrella organization (with coalitions such as the Barcelona Bars, Restaurants and Leisure Federation), vice-president Enric Gomà trusts that he can see the end of the tunnel and notes that overall reservations are quite &quot;lively&quot;, despite the fact that the customers &quot;get the most out of it&quot;.
However, the fun of partying has not decreased, no matter who pays.
Pakistan&#39;s nuclear program is a major concern in the US
Islamabad is producing nuclear weapons &quot;faster than any other country&quot;.
Wikileaks revelations confirm ties between the Taliban and Pakistan.
The content of the correspondence between the North American Embassy in Pakistan and the US Department of State, revealed by the Internet portal Wikileaks, confirms the enormous concerns of Pakistan&#39;s nuclear program in Washington.
On the margins of the clarifying and juicy details offered by the documents on the content of the talks and the mindset of the accredited North American diplomats in Islamabad, they reveal that the cooperation between the two countries in matters of nuclear security is not increasing, but on the contrary &quot;decreasing&quot;. , and that the unstable Asian country is producing more nuclear weapons &quot;at a faster pace than any other country.&quot;
In particular, the nature of Pakistan&#39;s nuclear program - that the weapons are not assembled but rather stored individually to make them more difficult to destroy in the event of an attack - is giving Washington sleepless nights.
Ambassador to Pakistan Anne W. Patterson lists the following risks in a report ahead of the visit of former National Security Council chief James Jones: &quot;The proximity of some nuclear facilities to the area attacked by the Taliban, the likely dispersal of nuclear materials and the vulnerability of the transport of nuclear material&quot;.
The large numbers of people involved in nuclear arsenals and missile programs are no longer viewed not only by the US but also by Russia as sprawling and a reason to exercise caution.
&quot;Pakistan needs to hire strictly religious personnel to guard nuclear facilities; due to the low educational and cultural level, extremist organizations have more opportunities to recruit people who work on nuclear or missile programs,&quot; Russian foreign ministry expert Yuri Korolev said in a briefing with its North American counterparts.
What is new about the documentary unveiled by Julian Assange&#39;s web portal is that US-Pakistan cooperation on nuclear proliferation is waning and the increased pace at which Pakistan is producing nuclear weapons.
In May, an embassy office, which describes communication with Pakistan as &quot;frustrating,&quot; said: &quot;Often there is no transparency; offers of help go unanswered or are rejected.&quot;
In another statement, Peter Lavoy, an official with the state intelligence agency for South Asia, confirmed that &quot;despite the economic catastrophe, Pakistan is producing nuclear weapons faster than any other country.&quot;
Ambassador Patterson asked Washington during a visit by Army Chief General Ashfaq Kayani to &quot;make it clear&quot; to those responsible that &quot;Pakistan&#39;s army must stop its tacit support of terrorist groups.&quot;
On the hunt for Wikileaks boss
Obama appoints a high-ranking officer in charge of counterterrorism to prevent new disclosures.
Interpol issues red alert to track and locate Assange.
Everything related to Wikileaks and its founder, Jullian Assange, forms a complicated maze in which the facts are difficult to clarify.
Interpol yesterday issued a &quot;red alert&quot; to &quot;find and prosecute&quot; Assange.
However, this is not a traditional arrest warrant.
Also, it&#39;s not new, it&#39;s from November 20th.
It also has nothing to do with the recent disclosure of over four million US diplomatic documents, but with the allegations of sexual abuse the Australian is facing in Sweden.
Furthermore, the lawyer for Wikileaks founder, Mark Stephens, assures that &quot;the police know where and how to contact Mr. Assange.&quot;
Already on the 20th, the international police agency based in Lyon (France) issued the order at Sweden&#39;s request, but it was not announced until yesterday after the Swedish authorities received the authorization.
That&#39;s the way things are. The 188 Interpol countries are instructed to identify and locate Assange &quot;in order to provisionally arrest and extradite him.&quot;
Although Interpol cannot order the arrest of an individual affected by a red alert, the organization says many member countries view the red alert as a warrant for arrest - to be carried out by national police - particularly if they have a bilateral extradition treaty. as is the case of Sweden and England, where Assange is believed to be.
The move outraged Assange&#39;s lawyers, who gestured to publish a letter informing them that the 39-year-old founder of Wikileaks is ready to answer questions from the Swedish authorities via video conference.
They also recall that Assange applied to leave Sweden and was granted permission by the prosecutor, who has been compared to the legendary Lavrentiy Pavlovich Beria, Stalin&#39;s chief of security.
&quot;This is like a hunt, not a legal prosecution,&quot; the letter said.
While the world is looking for him - and his mother from Australia pleads her son&#39;s innocence - Assange is in an unknown location, but not in silence.
On Monday, he gave an interview to the head of Time magazine via Skype from an unspecified location. During the meeting, he requested the resignation of US Secretary of State Hillary Clinton.
&quot;If it can be shown that she was responsible for ordering North American diplomats to spy on the UN in violation of international agreements signed by the US, she would have to resign,&quot; he said.
His opinion was condemned yesterday by White House Press Secretary Robert Gibbs, who called the request to resign &quot;ridiculous and absurd&quot;.
&quot;I&#39;m not sure why we should value the opinion of a guy with a website,&quot; he told CNN.
Obama himself has tasked a senior anti-terrorist official, Russell Travers, with preventing new disclosures of documents.
President Barack Obama&#39;s spokesman&#39;s attempt to de-emphasise Assange is at odds with the views conservative politicians and commentators are proclaiming these days.
Congressman Peter King, who will chair the House National Security Committee from January, has called on the State Department to investigate the possibility of listing Wikileaks as a terrorist organization &quot;to seize their funds and anyone who supports them or makes a contribution to pursue.&quot;
Tom Flanagan, adviser to Canadian President Stephen Harper, had gone further and had to retract his statement that Assange &quot;must be assassinated&quot;.
&quot;Obama would have to turn him into a target and use an unmanned plane or something.&quot;
The one who didn&#39;t apologize was Mike Huckabee, Baptist minister, former governor of Arkansas and possible presidential candidate.
&quot;Whoever it was that leaked information in government is guilty of treason and anything other than execution is too light a sentence,&quot; he told Fox.
Puigcercós, with a nod to those close to Carod, seeks peace in the ERC
The Republican leader allows the party to hold a secret ballot on his continued tenure.
Huguet proposes a more pluralistic government and the end of the general assembly principle.
Joan Puigcercós seems to have found a recipe for avoiding, for the umpteenth time, an internal turmoil in the ranks of the directionless ERC after losing 11 MPs and half the electorate.
