The USA is changing the rules for obtaining a visa
Before their interview at the consulate, the persons must present themselves to the service points for visa applications; Costs will be waiting times are shortened.
Effective January 10, 2011, procedures for applying for a visa at the United States Embassy and Consulates are changing.
Under the new procedure, most applicants must present themselves to the Visa Application Service Center (ASC, the initials in English) before their interview at the consulate.
The ASC staff takes the applicant&#39;s biometric data, which is checked by the consulate before the interview.
The new process has certain advantages for aspirants, including:
The total cost of visa processing is reduced because it is no longer necessary to pay separately for the appointment, the processing of the visa application and the transport service with which the document is handed over.
The applicant makes only a single payment covering the three services.
The current price remains unchanged: the equivalent of $140 for tourist visas, $150 for visas with application (including temporary worker visas) and $390 for traders and investors.
Those who only want to extend their visa do not need to have an interview at the consulate, they just need to present themselves at the nearest ASC, where they will present their documents and their fingerprints will be taken.
Since the biometric data is collected at the ASC, applicants who need a second appointment for the interview at the consulate have less time there than before.
Those who apply for visas at the consulates of Ciudad Juárez, Monterrey and Nuevo Laredo no longer have to pay the $26 service surcharge.
Additional information about the new visa application process can be found at the following website: http://mexico.usembassy.gov/boletines/sp101201_Visas-FAQs.html
