Vengeful hackers and busy spies
The WikiLeaks affair has a double meaning.
On one side it has emerged as an obvious scandal, a scandal that is merely a scandal in the sense of hypocrisy that governs relations between states, citizens and the press.
On the other hand, it heralds profound changes at the international level, and a foretaste of the future dominated by regression.
But let&#39;s go in order.
The first aspect of WikiLeaks is the acknowledgment of the fact that any file produced by any intelligence agency (of any nation) consists entirely of newspaper clippings.
The &quot;extraordinary&quot; American revelations about Berlusconi&#39;s sexual habits throw up nothing more than what you&#39;ve been reading for months in any journal (except those owned by Berlusconi) and Gaddafi&#39;s chillingly caricatured profile has long provided cabaret artists with material for their skits.
The rule according to which the secret dossiers can only consist of already known news is essential for the dynamics of the secret services, and not only in this century.
If you go to a library devoted to esoteric publications, you will find that each work (on the Grail, the Mystery of Rennes-le-Chateau, the Templars, or the Rosicrucians) repeats exactly what is already written in previous works became.
This is not only because the author of occult texts does not want to publish research (nor because he does not know where to find news about the non-existent), but because those who devote themselves to the occult think of nothing other than believe what they already know and validate what they have already learned.
This is also Dan Brown&#39;s mechanism for success.
Likewise the secret files.
The informant is lazy, and lazy (or dull-witted) is the head of the secret service (otherwise he could be whatever, e.g. editor at Liberation), who only accepts as true what he admits.
The top-secret information on Berlusconi that the American embassy in Rome had sent to the State Department was the same as that published by Newsweek the week before.
So why was there such a fuss about the disclosures of these dossiers?
On one side these state what every educated person already knows, namely that the embassies - at least since the end of the Second World War and since then also the heads of government can phone each other or take a plane to meet for dinner - perform their diplomatic function have lost and, with the exception of a few small representation tasks, have turned into spy centers.
Any viewer of investigative films knows this very well, and it is not out of hypocrisy that one pretends to ignore it.
Still, to repeat it publicly violates the task of hypocrisy and serves to cast American diplomacy in a bad light.
Second, the idea that any hacker can tap into the deepest secrets of the most powerful country in the world is a major blow to the prestige of the Department of State.
In addition, the scandal does not bring the victims so much as the &quot;executioners&quot; in distress.
But let&#39;s get into the profound nature of what happened.
Back in Orwell&#39;s day, all power could be concentrated like a Big Brother controlling every gesture of his subjects.
Orwell&#39;s prophecy might have turned out to be perfectly correct since then, where thanks to the phone one can control every movement, every transaction made, the hotel visited, the highway chosen and so on; the citizen would become a total victim of the eye of power.
But if you consider what is happening today, that even the secret crypts of power can no longer escape the control of a hacker, the patrol ceases to be one-way and becomes circular.
The Force controls every citizen, but every citizen, or at least the hacker - chosen to be the citizen&#39;s avenger - can learn the mysteries of the force.
But how can a power survive that is no longer able to keep its own secrets?
True, Georg Simmel already said that a real secret is an empty secret (and an empty secret can never be revealed); it is also true that any knowledge of the character of Berlusconi or Merkel is essentially a secret free of secret, since it reveals the public sphere; but to reveal, WikiLeaks-style, that Hillary Clinton&#39;s secrets were empty secrets is to strip her of all power.
WikiLeaks has wronged neither Sarkozy nor Merkel, but it has wronged Clinton and Obama.
What will be the consequences of this insult inflicted on such a mighty power?
It&#39;s obvious that states will no longer post any reserved information online - that would be tantamount to a notice posted on the street corner.
But it is equally obvious that with current technologies it is futile to hope to keep confidential reports secret over the phone.
Nothing is easier than finding out if and when a head of state has been on an airplane and contacted one of his colleagues.
How could private relationships intended only for certain ears be maintained in the future?
I am well aware that my prediction sounds sci-fi and novel-like at the moment, but I feel compelled to imagine the government agents secretly bustling along uncontrollable march routes, their communications nowhere but in mere memory carrying it with them and, moreover, hiding in the heel of their shoes the little written information they received.
The information would be stored in a single copy in locked drawers: basically, Watergate&#39;s espionage attempt had less success than WikiLeaks.
I had the opportunity to write that technology nowadays advances like a cancer: backwards.
A century after the wireless telegraph revolutionized communications, the Internet recreates a wire (telephone) telegraph.
The (analogue) videocassettes had allowed film researchers to explore a film tape by tape, rewinding from back to front and uncovering all the mysteries of the montage, while the (numerical) CDs today only allow you to jump from chapter to chapter , i.e. in macro portions.
The high-speed trains take you from Rome to Milan in three hours, while by plane it takes three and a half hours, including changes.
It is therefore not unusual that politics and communication technology are coming back to cars and horses.
One last observation.
In earlier times, the press tried to understand what secrets were forged between embassies.
Currently, it is the embassies that are demanding confidential information from the press.
Climate: how France sugarcoats its financial promises
A year on from the Copenhagen Accord, it is time to examine the delivery of fast-paced funding promises (also called &quot;fast start&quot; or premature funding) implemented by developing countries.
And already the coarse French rhetoric has been uncovered.
With the Copenhagen Treaty, developing countries committed to providing $30 billion between 2010 and 2012.
The EU has pledged 7.2 billion euros over three years, France 1.26 billion euros (ie 420 million per year).
On the occasion of the opening of COP16, the EU pulled out all the stops to convince its partners of the fact of its commitment to Fast Start funding: detailed progress report from its Member States, press conference, major side events, leaflet distribution.
Operation Transparency is remarkable and valued precisely for its intrinsic value: developing countries and civil society would like all developed countries to do the same thing with the same level of precision.
The EU announces it released €2.2 billion in 2010, putting it on track to pay respect to its €7.2 billion commitment in 2012.
But if you look into the details, things are a little more complicated.
This money, according to the Copenhagen Accord, should be &quot;new and additional&quot; to ensure that an additional effort has been put in without being detrimental to Official Development Assistance.
Unfortunately, there is no consensus on what &quot;new and additional&quot; means.
While the EU Commission had proposed harmonization, certain member states, including France, blocked the procedure.
Today, everyone chooses the benchmark that they consider best.
For example, the EU Commission has chosen the benchmark for 2009: international funding will be maintained and will add 150 million over three years as part of the &quot;Fast-Start&quot; funding.
Other countries have chosen similar benchmarks, either in terms of year or ODA level terms.
Conversely, France considered the 2010 financing of &quot;all new projects&quot; to be &quot;new and additional&quot;.
In other words, there are no benchmarks in the previous year&#39;s spending or at the global level of official development assistance.
More specifically, the total amount of French support to developing countries may remain stable (or decrease) - France pretends to honor its commitment regarding &quot;new and additional&quot; financing.
Another crucial element is the breakdown into donations and loans.
There is no rule yet, and everyone chooses their calculation mode.
Some, such as France, consider €1 borrowed to be equivalent to €1 donated.
Obviously, this is difficult to justify: the effort is not comparable.
If the use of loans can be justified for certain viable investments (often emission control projects based on the most effective technology), it is deceptive to present the euro that one collects as the equivalent of a donated euro... Moreover, it should only the cost of the loan to the lender country counts as an exposure (ie the equivalent of an interest rate).
But France has nothing but the following reflection in mind: it &quot;respects&quot; its commitment of 420 million euros by borrowing 91.5% (389.8 million euros) and donating 8.5% (36.1 million euros). ) - see also the EU document to see for yourself.
France is the only country in the EU that makes extensive use of loans.
Germany demands 46%, while Denmark, the Netherlands or Slovakia (among others) meet their commitments at 100% with donations.
In other words, if the vast majority of the European Union spends €1 to meet their commitments, France pays just 10 cents and sees it as a comparable bet.
Nice hocus pocus!
All in all, France operates in its Fast Start financing with a double swindle: partly with an evolution of the action over time and partly with the reality of the financial commitment.
France manages to make believe it has spent 420m &#39;new and additional&#39; million in line with its promises, saving 36.1m euros in the process.
The Treasury&#39;s manipulation (since it seems that it was Bercy who carried out the arbitrage) could have a doubly negative effect; once within the EU (why do the other member states continue to donate when it is enough to borrow?) and then in the negotiations, since the developing countries cannot be completely fooled...
The chapter on premature financing is only a small question for a relatively short time compared to the entirety of discussions about the climate.
But it could be a drop too many in the UNFCCC&#39;s immense machinery.
Let&#39;s hope this won&#39;t be the case.
Whatever the case, it&#39;s imperative to learn the lesson from this first year of premature funding.
First and foremost, France could announce a change in its accounting method for the years 2011 and 2012, in a spirit of respect for its commitments and balancing justice with the other countries of the European Union.
Above all, France could advance the debate on the issue of long-term financing (another crucial issue currently under discussion): there is no escaping the issue of &quot;settlement&quot; or the way in which its loans are accounted for.
France could change its position to be as progressive on the issues as it is on other things.
So the hope rests on the new environment minister, Kosciusko-Morizet, who is due to arrive in Cancun next week.
A surprise announcement of France&#39;s Fast-Start and its vision of &quot;clearance&quot; and the use of loans would inherently boost the international confidence needed for further discussion.
Alert - pesticides ingested by children
A 10-year-old child ingests 81 different chemical substances throughout the day, according to a study published Wednesday by the Générations Futures association (former movement to protect the rights and respect of future generations).
The association, which explains that its results &quot;given the small number of samples analyzed do not represent a statistically significant value, but are illustrative of the problem addressed&quot;, had between July and September, usually within four, by a child of around ten at mealtimes bought the food consumed plus a snack in the supermarkets in Oise and Paris.
These typical meals - including the official recommendations of five pieces of fresh fruit and fruit, three dairy products and 1.5 liters of water per day - have been studied, as well as sweets, by laboratories looking for chemicals, pesticides, heavy metals and other pollutants.
The plate tally is staggering: 81 chemical substances, including 42 classified as possibly or probably carcinogenic and five classified as definitely carcinogenic, as well as 37 substances with endocrine disruptors, according to studies by several institutions such as the International Cancer Research Center.
&quot;Even if, in almost all cases, the legal limits for each chemical substance ingested individually are not exceeded, this survey provides a very good indication of the reality of the consumer&#39;s possible exposure to carcinogenic or endocrine-disrupting substances is worrisome,&quot; notes the association.
Already at breakfast, the butter and tea with milk alone already contain more than ten of the potentially carcinogenic residues and three known to be carcinogenic, as well as more than twenty residues that can impair the endocrine system.
The apple imported from Brazil, intended as a snack for the study, shows traces of six chemical substances, including a fungicide banned in France.
The same applies to the green beans from Kenya, included in the lunch, in which the study found traces of an insecticide that is strictly banned in the EU.
In addition, the ground beef, canned tuna, even the baguette and chewing gum were peppered with pesticides and other chemicals.
The analyzes revealed the presence of nitrates and chloroform in the tap water.
At dinner, the salmon steak was the &quot;richest&quot; with 34 chemical residues found, and even the plastic plate used to reheat the meal in the microwave was not uncontaminated.
The ultimate risk of this &quot;toxic cocktail&quot; to consumers &quot;is likely to be underestimated,&quot; according to the study.
For its part, the &quot;Alliance Europe Ecologie-Les Verts&quot; (EE-LV) has proposed &quot;given the urgency of the situation&quot; to introduce a moratorium on the use of pesticides in order to stop the &quot;increase in civilization diseases&quot;.
In July, a study by the European Food Safety Authority (EFSA) related to the presence of residues had identified 365 different pesticides identified in fruits and vegetables consumed in Europe, including 76 in cereals.
